uiring them to chase 5 other links first\n- Keep code examples concrete and copy-pasteable\n\n## Execution Model\n\nOne document (or tight group) at a time. For each:\n1. Read the current document\n2. Understand audience and use case\n3. Rewrite following the guidelines\n4. Commit on a feature branch with `gh auth switch --user linuxdynasty`\n\n---\n\n## Scope 1: Root-Level Documents\n\n### 1.1 — CONTRIBUTING.md\n- **Audience**: External contributors, new team members\n- **Current issues**: Says \"in the middle of a product and identity cleanup\" (outdated), uses `pip install -e` instead of `uv sync`, duplicates docs/docs/contributing.md\n- **What to do**: Rewrite as the canonical contributing guide. Use `uv sync` for setup. Remove \"cleanup\" language. Keep it concise — PR rules, dev setup, running checks, submitting. Remove duplication by making docs/docs/contributing.md point here or vice versa.\n\n### 1.2 — TESTING.md\n- **Audience**: Contributors, CI engineers\n- **Current issues**: Minor — good structure but thin. Could explain the test philosophy more.\n- **What to do**: Light polish. Tighten prose, ensure commands are current, update \"Current Gaps\" if any have been closed.\n\n### 1.3 — SECURITY.md\n- **Audience**: Security researchers, operators\n- **Current issues**: Generic template structure.\n- **What to do**: Light polish. Keep it short but make it sound like we wrote it.\n\n### 1.4 — ACKNOWLEDGMENTS.md\n- **Audience**: Community, legal\n- **Current issues**: Fine as-is but very minimal.\n- **What to do**: Light polish only.\n\n---\n\n## Scope 2: Docs Site — Core Pages\n\n### 2.1 — docs/docs/index.md\n- **Audience**: Everyone (landing page)\n- **What to do**: Light polish. Align opening with the new README tone.\n\n### 2.2 — docs/docs/architecture.md\n- **Audience**: Engineers, architects\n- **Current issues**: Dense. \"Does not ship a marketing site\" is defensive. Mermaid diagram is good.\n- **What to do**: Moderate rewrite. Reframe section 2 positi