ady has repo-side validation harnesses and claims Bolt/Cypher + MVCC snapshot isolation.\n  - `ArcadeDB`: include as the second primary PoC candidate because it supports Cypher and is the most likely non-Redis path to reduce rewrite while still improving write concurrency.\n  - `FalkorDB`: keep as a secondary candidate only if you are willing to accept a non-Bolt path and adapter work; its official client model is Redis-based and its Bolt support is explicitly experimental.\n  - `Memgraph`: de-prioritize for this problem unless another constraint dominates, because its HA model keeps one `MAIN` handling all writes, which does not remove your current single-writer bottleneck.\n\n- Deliver two final rankings:\n  - `Least rewrite`: `NornicDB`, `ArcadeDB`, `Memgraph`, `FalkorDB`\n  - `Max write scale`: `NornicDB`, `ArcadeDB`, `FalkorDB`, `Memgraph`\n  - Mark any ordering based on incomplete vendor evidence as provisional and require a PoC to confirm.\n\n## Test Plan\n\n- Compatibility verification:\n  - Run the existing NornicDB compatibility and write benchmark scripts unchanged.\n  - Build equivalent smoke checks for other candidates around:\n    - schema bootstrap\n    - explicit `begin_transaction()/commit()/rollback()`\n    - `UNWIND` + `MERGE`\n    - `DETACH DELETE`\n    - `OPTIONAL MATCH`\n    - variable-length traversals\n    - fulltext create/query behavior\n\n- Write-path verification:\n  - Benchmark serial vs concurrent repository commits with `PCG_COMMIT_WORKERS > 1`\n  - Reject any backend that still funnels all writes through one leader for the ingest-heavy path\n\n- Decision gates:\n  - Fail a candidate if it cannot support the transaction semantics or query shapes PCG already uses\n  - Downgrade a candidate if it can work only through translation/adapters for schema or fulltext\n  - Prefer the backend that passes the repo’s Cypher surface with the smallest operational and code-change cost\n\n## Assumptions and Defaults\n\n- `NornicDB` refers to [`orneryd