          "text": "<proposed_plan>\n# PRD Review: Incremental Indexing Needs a Rewrite\n\n## Summary\nThe current PRD does **not** make sense as written.\n\n- Its core premise is wrong for steady-state sync. The live ingester already skips unchanged repos during `repo-sync-loop`; only cloned, updated, or resumable repos are selected for indexing in [sync_operations.py](/Users/allen/personal-repos/platform-context-graph/src/platform_context_graph/runtime/ingester/sync_operations.py#L78) and [git_sync_ops.py](/Users/allen/personal-repos/platform-context-graph/src/platform_context_graph/runtime/ingester/git_sync_ops.py#L335). The deployment runs `repo-sync-loop`, not `bootstrap-index`, in [statefulset.yaml](/Users/allen/personal-repos/platform-context-graph/deploy/helm/platform-context-graph/templates/statefulset.yaml#L44).\n- The real waste is **full delete/rebuild inside each changed repo**, which happens in [coordinator.py](/Users/allen/personal-repos/platform-context-graph/src/platform_context_graph/indexing/coordinator.py#L121), not “all 846 repos every interval.”\n- The proposed V1 correctness model is not acceptable. It explicitly allows missing incoming edges after incremental updates, and today’s finalization already only runs over selected snapshots in [graph_builder_indexing_execution.py](/Users/allen/personal-repos/platform-context-graph/src/platform_context_graph/tools/graph_builder_indexing_execution.py#L215). A revised PRD must not formalize stale graph state as success.\n\n## Revised PRD Direction\n- Rewrite the problem statement:\n  - `repo-sync-loop` already provides **repo-level incremental indexing** by skipping unchanged repos.\n  - The new goal is **file-level incremental indexing inside repos whose Git HEAD changed**, plus an optional later phase for cold-start/bootstrap optimization.\n- Keep Git change detection in the **repo-sync runtime**, not the coordinator.\n  - The runtime already owns fetch/reset and repo selection.\n  - The coordinator should receive a `RepositoryChangeSet` input, not re-query Git and not query Neo4j for sync truth.\n- Do **not** store `last_indexed_sha` or config-fingerprint state on the Neo4j `Repository` node.\n  - That is the wrong source of truth for ingestion control.\n  - Persist change-manifest/control state under repo-sync/checkpoint storage in `PCG_HOME`, alongside existing workspace/run state.\n- Make correctness the default:\n  - No mode may knowingly leave missing edges in the graph.\n  - If the implementation cannot prove the affected relationship closure is complete, it must fall back to **full repo rebuild** for that repo.\n\n## Phased Design\n- Phase 1: Runtime-side change manifests and accurate observability.\n  - Extend repo-sync to emit `RepositoryChangeSet {repo_path, old_sha, new_sha, added, modified, deleted, renamed, reason}` for repos already selected by current Git sync.\n  - Add runtime status/metrics for repo selection reason, old/new SHA, changed file counts, and fallback reason.\n  - This phase corrects the PRD and hardens the contract without changing indexing semantics yet.\n- Phase 2: Prerequisite for real file-level incremental.\n  - Introduce a stable entity-identity strategy for code entities that does not depend solely on line number.\n  - Current canonical content/entity IDs include `line_number` in [content/ingest.py](/Users/allen/personal-repos/platform-context-graph/src/platform_context_graph/content/ingest.py#L187), which makes many harmless edits look like delete+recreate and destroys inbound edges.\n  - Without this prerequisite, file-level incremental will be brittle and frequently degenerate to full rebuilds.\n- Phase 3: Safe file-level incremental for changed repos.\n  - Coordinator accepts optional `RepositoryChangeSet` inputs.\n  - For deleted files: delete file graph state and file content rows.\n  - For modified/added files: parse changed files, upsert/prune file-local entities, and rebuild only affected relationships.\n  - Fallback to full repo rebuild when:\n    - `.gitignore`, `.pcgignore`, `.gitmodules`, or index-affecting config changes\n    - diff unavailable/untrustworthy\n    - rename/move cases the identity model cannot preserve safely\n    - affected relationship closure cannot be derived completely\n- Phase 4: Optional startup/bootstrap optimization.\n  - Only if cold-start time is still a real problem after Phase 3.\n  - Optimize bootstrap/cold workspace behavior separately from steady-state sync; do not mix it into the same core incremental design.\n\n## Important Interface Changes\n- Add a repo-sync-owned `RepositoryChangeSet` type and pass it into indexing entrypoints for Git-backed runs.\n- Add `delete_file_content(repo_id, relative_path)` to the Postgres content provider.\n- Add repo-run diagnostics such as `index_mode`, `old_sha`, `new_sha`, changed/deleted counts, and fallback reason to checkpoint/runtime status.\n- Preserve current behavior for non-Git entrypoints:\n  - direct path indexing\n  - workspace/manual indexing\n  - watcher flows\n  These should continue to use existing behavior unless they explicitly provide a change manifest.\n\n## Test Plan\n- Verify no-op Git sync with hundreds of unchanged repos indexes `0` repos and records explicit skip reasons.\n- Verify changed-repo selection comes only from runtime Git diff/fetch state, not coordinator-side Git rechecks.\n- Verify file delete and rename handling removes both graph and content-store rows correctly.\n- Verify modified-file incremental updates preserve stable entities and their incoming edges when identity is unchanged.\n- Verify any case with incomplete affected-relationship closure falls back to full repo rebuild.\n- Verify `.gitignore` and `.pcgignore` changes trigger full-repo fallback, with repo-scoped `.gitignore` semantics preserved.\n\n## Assumptions and Defaults\n- Deployment concern is the steady-state Git ingester path, which already runs `repo-sync-loop`, not bootstrap.\n- Repo-local `.gitignore` behavior is already correct and remains unchanged.\n- Correctness wins over IO reduction: no “missing edges until next full reindex” acceptance criteria.\n- The current PRD should be replaced, not patched, because the current behavior and ownership boundaries are misstated.\n</proposed_plan>",
